bash-3.2$ man df
DF(1)                                                                           General Commands Manual                                                                          DF(1)

[1mNAME[0m
     [1mdf[0m – display free disk space

[1mSYNOPSIS[0m
     [1mdf[0m [[1m--libxo[0m] [[1m-b[0m | [1m-g[0m | [1m-H[0m | [1m-h[0m | [1m-k[0m | [1m-m[0m | [1m-P[0m] [[1m-acIilntY[0m] [[1m-,[0m] [[1m-T[0m [4mtype[24m] [[4mfile[24m | [4mfilesystem[24m [4m...[24m]

[1mLEGACY[0m [1mSYNOPSIS[0m
     [1mdf[0m [[1m--libxo[0m] [[1m-b[0m | [1m-g[0m | [1m-H[0m | [1m-h[0m | [1m-k[0m | [1m-m[0m | [1m-P[0m] [[1m-acIilnY[0m] [[1m-,[0m] [[1m-T[0m [4mtype[24m] [[1m-t[0m [4mtype[24m] [[4mfile[24m | [4mfilesystem[24m [4m...[24m]

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
     The [1mdf[0m utility displays statistics about the amount of free disk space on the specified mounted [4mfile[24m [4msystem[24m or on the file system of which [4mfile[24m is a part.  By default block
     counts are displayed with an assumed block size of 512 bytes.  If neither a file or a file system operand is specified, statistics for all mounted file systems are displayed
     (subject to the [1m-t[0m option below).

     The following options are available:

     [1m--libxo[0m
             Generate output via libxo(3) in a selection of different human and machine readable formats.  See xo_parse_args(3) for details on command line arguments.

     [1m-a[0m      Show all mount points, including those that were mounted with the MNT_IGNORE flag.  This is implied for file systems specified on the command line.

     [1m-b[0m      Explicitly use 512 byte blocks, overriding any BLOCKSIZE specification from the environment.  This is the same as the [1m-P[0m option.  The [1m-k[0m option overrides this option.

     [1m-c[0m      Display a grand total.

     [1m-g[0m      Use 1073741824 byte (1 Gibibyte) blocks rather than the default.  This overrides any BLOCKSIZE specification from the environment.

     [1m-h[0m      “Human-readable” output.  Use unit suffixes: Byte, Kibibyte, Mebibyte, Gibibyte, Tebibyte and Pebibyte (based on powers of 1024) in order to reduce the number of digits
             to four or fewer.  This applies to the Size, Used, and Avail columns only; the iused and ifree columns will be displayed in powers of 1000.

     [1m-H[0m, [1m--si[0m
             Same as [1m-h[0m but based on powers of 1000.

     [1m-I[0m      Suppress inode counts.  See [1m-i[0m below.

     [1m-i[0m      Include statistics on the number of free and used inodes.  In conjunction with the [1m-h[0m or [1m-H[0m options, the number of inodes is scaled by powers of 1000.  In case the
             filesystem has no inodes then ‘-’ is displayed instead of the usage percentage.

             This option is now the default to conform to Version 3 of the Single UNIX Specification (“SUSv3”).  Use [1m-I[0m to suppress this output.

     [1m-k[0m      Use 1024 byte (1 Kibibyte) blocks rather than the default.  This overrides the [1m-P[0m option and any BLOCKSIZE specification from the environment.

     [1m-l[0m      Select locally-mounted file system for display.  If used in combination with the [1m-T[0m [4mtype[24m option, file system types will be added or excluded acccording to the parameters
             of that option.

     [1m-m[0m      Use 1048576 byte (1 Mebibyte) blocks rather than the default.  This overrides any BLOCKSIZE specification from the environment.

     [1m-n[0m      Print out the previously obtained statistics from the file systems.  This option should be used if it is possible that one or more file systems are in a state such that
             they will not be able to provide statistics without a long delay.  When this option is specified, [1mdf[0m will not request new statistics from the file systems, but will
             respond with the possibly stale statistics that were previously obtained.

     [1m-P[0m      Explicitly use 512 byte blocks, overriding any BLOCKSIZE specification from the environment.  This is the same as the [1m-b[0m option.  The [1m-g[0m and [1m-k[0m options override this
             option.  In compatibility mode, this also suppresses inode counts.
